Nael — An Emacs major mode for Lean
***********************************

Nael is a set of packages extending GNU Emacs
(https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/) for editing Lean
(https://lean-lang.org) sources.  It is a radically refactored fork of
Lean4-Mode (https://github.com/leanprover-community/lean4-mode) with
focus on simplicity, modularity and integration into Emacs' core.  It's
still at an early stage of development.

   The ‘nael’ package defines a major mode.  In a modular, unobtrusive
way, it also defines simple and complex abbreviations per Abbrev
(https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/manual/html_node/emacs/Abbrevs.html)
and Skeleton
(https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/manual/html_node/autotype/)
respectively.  It teaches Emacs' built-in LSP
(https://microsoft.github.io/language-server-protocol/ Language Server
Protocol) client Eglot
(https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/manual/html_node/eglot/) about
Lean-specific LSP-extensions
(https://github.com/leanprover/lean4/blob/master/src/Lean/Data/Lsp/Extra.lean)
and tells ElDoc
(https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/manual/html_node/emacs/Programming-Language-Doc.html)
to display that information, similar to the “info view
(https://github.com/leanprover/vscode-lean4/blob/master/vscode-lean4/manual/manual.md#infoview)”
in vscode-lean
(https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=leanprover.lean4)
that many are familiar with.  For users who prefer the external package
lsp-mode (https://github.com/emacs-lsp/lsp-mode) as LSP client over
Eglot, there's the ‘nael-lsp’ package.

